    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-12T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-12T10:00:00-05:00" n="610"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d610">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/662: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-12T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 12, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. For the Secretary and Under Secretary. Information has come to me from what I
                    believe to be sure source that on January 27, Von Papen<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d610fn21">Franz von Papen, German Ambassador in Turkey.</note> sent
                    King of Sweden letter suggesting good offices in bringing about peace between
                    Greece and Italy and that negative reply was received yesterday.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
